english:
  title: Epitaph for An Goon, Vice Director of the Sungkyunkwan and Grand Commandant
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the spring of the sixth year of Hongzhi, the Erudite of the Hongmun Pavilion, Pyo Soyou, came to me weeping. He spoke through his tears: "My fellow graduate An Goon departed last autumn on imperial orders to oversee the fortification of Pyonghai. As his travels brought him to Gangneung, he retired for the night. By dawn, he was dead. His orphaned son bore his remains home, and we laid him to rest on the third day of the tenth month of this year in the Du-chuk village near Gwangju. Alas, though his body has descended into the realm below, his deeds and conduct in life cannot be buried with him. We must entrust them to words, that they endure forever. Who else but you should compose his memorial?"

    I straightened myself and sighed deeply: "An was my friend. When I served at the Pavilion of Literary Arts, An held a post in the Hanlin Academy. When An became an official of the Ministry of Justice, I rose to Vice Minister. When I became Chancellor of the National University, An became Vice Director of the same institution. An was my friend. I know no one better suited to judge his character. Therefore it is fitting that the commission comes to me."

    Based on the records, the gentleman was named An Peng-myeong, styled De-bo, and was a man of Gwangneung. His great-grandfather, the Prefect of the Bureau of Agriculture, was named An Gi. His grandfather, Deputy Governor of Gaesong, was named An Seong. His father, Inspector of the Censoriate, was named An Jongsaeng. He married the daughter of Hong Sae, Magistrate of the Ministry of Personnel, and was born in the third month of the year Jeongtongyeonmyo, now reaching the age of forty-six—how brief his life!

    An lost his father in youth. At seventeen he first took to learning. By twenty-two he passed the civil examination, and three years later was selected for the higher degree. How swift his rise! While a student at the National Academy, a sorceress claimed to carry an imperial decree and performed rituals at the Spirit Pond. All the scholars were outraged, yet none dared speak for fear of punishment. Only An stepped forward boldly and drove her away—such was his spirit.

    Upon entering service, he moved through the great ministries and bureaus, earning renown wherever he went. At the Ministry of Justice, he rendered verdicts with impartiality. Once a prisoner faced death though the law forbade it. The Magistrate was stern, and the other officials dared not contradict him. But An alone took up the matter, arguing with such clarity that the Magistrate saw his error, and the prisoner was spared. Many owed their lives to An in those days. Yet where law and human feeling permitted no exception, he held fast and never wavered.

    When appointed Vice Director of Sacrificial Rites, he managed the ceremonial fields with such devotion that he purified himself and personally sealed every offering to the gods. Once serving as Censor, he entered the royal lectures with Minister Yun Ho. Upon leaving, as they took their meal, the Minister called him by name informally. An did not respond, but went to the gate and submitted a memorial: "I and the Minister passed the examinations in the same year and have long been close. Yet as a Censor, I cannot suffer my name to be called across a public gathering—it suggests my standing is slight and I am beneath proper regard. I must request to be excused." Those who heard trembled. Such was his courage in office: he spoke freely and feared no power.

    An possessed a dignified nature, profound learning, and governed himself by principle. In all matters he showed conscientiousness, earning the love and respect of his peers. He was temperate and humble, never using his position to seek favor from nobles, and took no interest in accumulating wealth. His home remained simple and unadorned. He maintained a modest villa in Gwangju for his retirement, saying to others: "When a man ages, his resolve weakens. To cling shamefully to office brings ridicule—this I greatly fear." When he saw others in poverty, he helped them to the extent his means allowed. Kinfolk who arrived at his door, whether distant or near, high or low, received his sincere welcome. Witnessing another's virtue, he rejoiced as in his own achievement. But hearing of another's failing, his face would darken as if tasting bitter medicine. Such were his preferences. Alas, who could have foreseen that An would depart so soon?

    An married the daughter of Hong Gyekgang, Magistrate of the county, and fathered two sons and four daughters. His eldest daughter married the scholar Yi Ja; the second married the clan relative and Governor of Haksong. His elder son is named Gyeong-sun; the younger children are still young.

    The Epitaph reads:

    Heaven grants to humans talent and virtue,
    Yet cannot grant their bodies long life.
    Earth conceals the flesh and bone,
    But cannot extinguish the spirit.
    Though the master has passed,
    That which dies not endures.
    In the ruins of Gwangneung,
    In the village of Du-chuk,
    An uncanny radiance lingers still—
    The presence of the master's sacred ground.
  footnotes:
    - An Peng-myeong (安彭命, 1408-1453) was a prominent official of the early Joseon Dynasty, known for his integrity and judicial fairness.
    - The 'Spirit Pond' (泮水) refers to the ceremonial pond within the National Academy grounds, sacred to Confucian education.
    - The epitaph's final verse employs a Buddhist-inflected philosophy common to Korean literati of the period, suggesting that virtue transcends physical death.
